#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:20
msgid "#### Simple virtual machine creation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:22
msgid ""
"To create a virtual machine you will, if required, create a hard drive image "
"for it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:26
msgid "``` qemu-img create -f qcow2 disk.qcow2 8G ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:28
msgid ""
"Your virtual machine drive is now ready for use. You may launch a virtual "
"machine using this drive like so:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:32
msgid "``` qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -hda ./disk.qcow2 -m 4096 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:34
msgid ""
"Where `-enable-kvm` enables KVM virtualisation instead of using emulation; "
"`-hda ./disk.qcow2` attaches the disk image; and `-m 4096` allocates 4096MB "
"of RAM to the virtual machine."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:36
msgid "To attach a cdrom image, for example to install an operating system:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:40
msgid ""
"``` qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -hda ./disk.qcow2 -m 4096 -cdrom "
"./subgraph-os-alpha_2016-06-16_2.iso -boot d ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:42
msgid "#### Advanced virtual machine creation"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:44
msgid ""
"For more control and easier installation of Debian releases inside of a "
"virtual machine, one may use debootstrap to create pre installed images "
"without going through the installer process."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:46
msgid ""
"Let's start by creating an 8GB raw sparse image for our VM, then format and "
"mount it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:53
msgid ""
"``` truncate --size 8G ./disk.img # Here you could decide to create a proper "
"partition table if you wanted... or not...  /sbin/mkfs.ext4 ./disk.img sudo "
"mount -o loop ./disk.img /mnt ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:55
msgid ""
"It's worth nothing that you should have enough free disk space for the image "
"you create (and possible twice as much if you want to convert it later on)."
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:57
msgid "However, the truncated image will only take as much as space as required:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:64
msgid ""
"``` du -sh disk.img 189M\tdisk.img du --apparent-size -sh disk.img "
"8.0G\tdisk.img ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:66
msgid ""
"Now that we have an image created and mounted, we can use debootstrap to "
"expand a basic install into it:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:69
msgid "``` sudo debootstrap --variant=mintbase --include=systemd-sysv stretch /mnt"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:72
msgid "# And set a root password sudo chroot /mnt passwd"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:77
msgid ""
"# Create a standard fstab sudo tee /mnt/etc/fstab << EOL "
"/dev/sda\t/\text4\tdefaults,errors=remount-ro\t0\t1 EOL"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:86
msgid ""
"# Let's download the subgraph grsec kernel and install it cd /tmp apt-get "
"download linux-{image,headers}-grsec-amd64-subgraph "
"linux-{image,headers}-$(uname -r)  sudo cp ./linux-{image,headers}-$(uname "
"-r) /mnt/tmp sudo chroot /mnt $ dpkg -i /tmp/linux-{image,headers}-* $ "
"update-initramfs -u -k all $ exit"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:89
msgid ""
"# Now we grab a copy of the kernel and initramfs we just installed to boot "
"the system cp /mnt/boot/vmlinuz-<version>-amd64 "
"/mnt/boot/initrd.img-<version>-amd64 /home/user/path/to/vm"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:94
msgid "# After, we will sync and umount sync sudo umount /mnt ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:96
msgid ""
"Once done, we can use it as is with Qemu/KVM, or if you prefer it can be "
"converted to a qcow2 image for convenience:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:100
msgid "``` qemu-img convert -f raw -O qcow2 ./disk.img ./disk.qcow2 ```"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:102
msgid "We can now launch our image:"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:109
#, no-wrap
msgid ""
"```\n"
"qemu-system-x86_64 -enable-kvm -hda ./disk.qcow2 \\\n"
"\t-kernel ./vmlinuz-<version>-amd64 \\\n"
"\t-initrd ./initrd.img-<version>-amd64 \\\n"
"\t-append root=/dev/sda\n"
"```\n"
msgstr ""

#. type: Plain text
#: 05_features_and_advanced_usage_07_virtualmachines.md:111
msgid ""
"If you want to install grub to keep the kernel and initrd images inside the "
"virtual machine you'll have to create a full partition table, and "
"potentially a separate /boot partition. But this is out of scope for this "
"short tutorial."
msgstr ""

